  "topic_name": "Simple Machines",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Simple machines are devices that make work easier by changing the direction or amount of force needed. There are six types of simple machines: lever, pulley, wheel and axle, inclined plane, wedge, and screw. A lever is a rod that rotates around a fixed point called the fulcrum (examples: see-saw, scissors, bottle opener). An inclined plane is a sloped surface that makes it easier to move objects up or down (examples: ramps, slides). A wedge is like two inclined planes joined together and is used for cutting or splitting (examples: knife, axe, nail). A pulley is a wheel with a rope that helps lift heavy objects (examples: flagpole, well). A wheel and axle is a wheel attached to a rod and helps move or turn things (examples: door knob, steering wheel). A screw is an inclined plane wrapped around a cylinder and is used for holding things together (examples: screws, jar lids).",
    "rules": [
      "Simple machines make work easier",
      "Six simple machines: lever, pulley, wheel and axle, inclined plane, wedge, screw",
      "Lever: rod rotating around a fixed point (fulcrum)",
      "Lever examples: see-saw, scissors, bottle opener, pliers",
